Hi,

As the name &quot;unit testing&quot; suggests, your best bet is to test each of your
components one by one, in isolation.  But as you say, that can be tricky
when the input to your component needs to come from some other component.
In these cases you may find it worthwhile to invest the time to create test
stubs for these objects.

Here&#39;s an elementary example:  Suppose you&#39;re testing the &quot;foo&quot; method of
your &quot;Comp&quot; component.  However, this method requires a &quot;Bar&quot; object to be
passed in, and the only way to get one of these is to interact with some
other component(s)--something of a unit-testing &quot;no-no.&quot;

    public interface Comp {
        public void foo(Bar bar);
    }

What you want to do is create another implementation of the Bar interface
called TestBar, which returns dummy test data instead of doing actual work.
(If Bar is not already an interface, renaming it something like BarImpl and
making Bar an interface!)  Then create an instance of this TestBar object to
test your foo() method with.

Does this help, or is it too elementary?

Kevin



-----Original Message-----
From: Egger, Wolfgang [mailto:beuys@...]
Sent: Thursday, December 21, 2000 12:31 AM
